            {"q": "Which of the following may produce a virtual image? I. Convex Mirror II. Concave Mirror III. Convex Lens IV. Concave Lens", "opts": ["I, IV only", "I, III only", "I, II, IV only", "I, II, III, IV"], "ans": 3, "exp": "All four optical devices can produce virtual images under certain conditions."},
            {"q": "Light waves of different frequencies will have different:", "opts": ["Speeds", "Amplitude", "Colours", "Intensities"], "ans": 2, "exp": "Different frequencies of light correspond to different colours. In vacuum, all light travels at the same speed."},
            {"q": "The horizontal component of the Earth's magnetic field is: I. Zero at the magnetic equator II. Zero at the magnetic poles III. Maximum at the magnetic equator IV. Maximum at the magnetic poles", "opts": ["I only", "II only", "II, III only", "I, IV only"], "ans": 2, "exp": "The horizontal component is maximum at the equator (III) and zero at the poles (II). So II and III are correct."},
            {"q": "The following radiations are electrically neutral EXCEPT:", "opts": ["α-rays", "γ-rays", "X-rays", "Neutrons"], "ans": 0, "exp": "Alpha (α) particles consist of 2 protons and 2 neutrons, giving them a charge of +2. They are NOT electrically neutral. Gamma rays, X-rays, and neutrons are neutral."},
            {"q": "The centripetal acceleration of an object at constant speed in circular path is: I. Directly proportional to speed II. Directly proportional to mass III. Directly proportional to speed² IV. Inversely proportional to radius", "opts": ["I, II only", "II, III, IV only", "III, IV only", "II, III only"], "ans": 2, "exp": "Centripetal acceleration a = v²/r. So a ∝ v² (III correct) and a ∝ 1/r (IV correct). Mass has no effect. So III and IV only."},
            {"q": "The escape velocity from a planet: I. Increases with mass of object II. Increases with mass of planet III. Is smaller on the moon than on Earth", "opts": ["I only", "II only", "II, III only", "I, II, III"], "ans": 2, "exp": "Escape velocity v = √(2GM/R). Depends on planet mass (M) and radius (R), NOT mass of escaping object. Moon has smaller mass so smaller escape velocity. So II and III."},
            {"q": "12V battery of internal resistance 0.1Ω is connected across a lamp of resistance R. If current of 10A flows, the value of R is:", "opts": ["0.9Ω", "1.0Ω", "1.1Ω", "1.2Ω"], "ans": 2, "exp": "V = I(R + r) → 12 = 10(R + 0.1) → R + 0.1 = 1.2 → R = 1.1Ω"},
            {"q": "An AC with RMS voltage of 50V has frequency of 60Hz. The AC is represented by:", "opts": ["v=50sin60πt", "v=50sin120πt", "v=70.7sin60πt", "v=70.7sin120πt"], "ans": 3, "exp": "Peak voltage V₀ = 50√2 ≈ 70.7V. Angular frequency ω = 2πf = 120π. So v = 70.7sin(120πt)."},
            {"q": "Celsius and Fahrenheit scales read the same at:", "opts": ["-80°", "-40°", "0°", "40°"], "ans": 1, "exp": "Setting F = C: C = (9/5)C + 32 → -32 = (4/5)C → C = -40°. At -40°, both scales read the same."},
            {"q": "In an electric kettle, the heating element is at the bottom because: I. Cold water is denser than hot water II. Heat is transmitted by convection III. Heat is quickly conducted IV. Loss to surroundings is minimized", "opts": ["I, II only", "III, IV only", "I, II, III only", "I, II, IV only"], "ans": 3, "exp": "Cold water sinks (I), hot water rises creating convection currents (II), and placing element at bottom minimizes heat loss (IV). Conduction is not the primary mechanism."},
            {"q": "A body initially at rest falls freely under gravity. If g = 10m/s², the distance covered in the fourth second is:", "opts": ["35m", "40m", "45m", "80m"], "ans": 0, "exp": "Distance in nth second: sₙ = g(2n-1)/2 = 10(2×4-1)/2 = 10×7/2 = 35m."},
            {"q": "Which of the following waves cannot be polarized?", "opts": ["Infra-red", "Yellow light", "X-rays", "Sound"], "ans": 3, "exp": "Sound waves are longitudinal (particles vibrate along direction of propagation) and cannot be polarized. EM waves (IR, visible, X-rays) are transverse and can be polarized."},
